It’s a big Shame for Cricket The ongoing second test match between India and South Africa at Newlands cricket ground has raised concerns about the quality of the pitch and the role of the curator. Unusual for a day one of a test match, 23 wickets fell for only 271 runs, leaving many cricket enthusiasts, including myself, perplexed. While commentators and news outlets have heaped praise on the bowlers' performances, labeling it a "bowlers' paradise" and celebrating their brilliance, there appears to be a lack of acknowledgement regarding the substandard pitch prepared by Cricket South Africa. This raises questions about potential biases and double standards when it comes to evaluating pitches. It is worth considering how similar situations have been criticized in the past. When Indian spinners have achieved a five-wicket haul on pitches deemed favorable to them on day 3 or 4 of a test match , there have been widespread complaints about the poor standards and unplayability of the pitches. It is essential to maintain consistency and fairness in assessing pitches across different cricketing nations. The responsibility for pitch preparation lies with the respective cricket boards, in this case, Cricket South Africa. If there are concerns about the quality of the pitch at Newlands, it is valid to express disappointment and address these concerns to the relevant governing body, such as the International Cricket Council (ICC), who can investigate the matter. It is important to recognize that while the Newlands pitch may have produced an unusual match, it also showcased the skills and abilities of the bowlers, who were able to capitalize on the challenging conditions. However, it is crucial for cricket authorities to strike a balance that provides a fair and competitive playing field while upholding the integrity and quality of Test cricket. To foster a healthy cricketing environment, open discussions about pitch conditions are necessary, and continuous efforts should be made to improve the overall standard and experience of Test cricket. It is within the realm of possibility for the ICC and Cricket South Africa to address concerns and to ensure that future pitches meet the expected standards of the game. Let’s hope that the 2nd test will end on day 2
